Fourteen other persons will be tried, including Joao Vaccari Neto, former treasurer of the Workers' Party in Brazil, and Renato de Souza Duque, former president of the Petrobras business services.
Dirceu is the oldest member of the ruling Workers Party taken in custody for connections to this scheme.
Dirceu served as chief of the former president Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva between 2003 and 2005.
He was arrested early August at home, where he was already under house arrest, with an 11-year sentence for involvement in a voting scheme in Congress over 10 years ago.
The prosecutors said Dirceu developed the Petrobras bribe-taking scheme, accepted bribes while in operation and continued to receive payments from entrepreneurs after it was closed at the end of 2013 for the scandal of the votes purchased.
According to prosecutors, the Petrobras scheme involved approximately $2 billion in bribe and other illegal funds.
Part of that money would have returned to the campaign fund of the ruling party and their allies.
It would also include bribes to Petrobras directors in exchange for inflated contracts.
‘miraculous’ recovery of a surviving student from the Peshawar massacre
A child paralyzed after being shot four times in Pakistan's worst terrorist attack succeeded in a "miraculous" recovery after following treatment in the United Kingdom.
Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, 13-year-old, the doctors in Pakistan had told him he'd never be able to go again.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the public school of the Peshawar army last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for the operation, will be discharged later from the hospital.
Just nine months ago, an ordinary morning on Tuesday, Mohamed sat at first aid and listened carefully to his teachers.
Even then, seven armed men disguised in uniforms of security officers entered public military school.
They wore belts with explosives and had a simple mission to accomplish: to kill all men, women and children out of the way.
"I can't forget what happened that day," Mohamed says with a rough look.
I was sitting in the amphitheater, asking questions... then I heard gunshots out.
The terrorists went inside and started killing. Our teacher was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater as the carnage unfolds.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, yelling at him.
He said "oh, brother, save me."
I held him by the hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he in the head.
Most of the people killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed remembers that immediately after that he passed out and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed paralyzed from the brass down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then the doctors in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to go.
"When I saw him, I felt how my soul came out," says Sher Khan, Mohamed's father.
Those nine months were the hardest of my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so passionate about cricket would never be able to use his feet again.
They campaigned and called for help from Pakistani television, attracting support from famous people like Imran Khan, a cricket player who became a politician.
In the end, they managed to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and provide treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
The neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "fearing" when he arrived at the hospital.
“He had spent the last [a few] months lying in bed without being able to move on one side,” Malik says.
He was weak, he had put a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in a very good shape.
A vertebrae at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in the shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team were able to rewire the nerve endings and rebuild the destroyed part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Just a week after the operation, Mohamed stood up and started to step in and walk.
We weren't expecting such a good result.
It was a miracle," he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and start the long recovery process.
Mohamed challenged fate and began to go again
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
However, it is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance to live," he says, showing the weapons images drawn by him next to school textbooks and pens
Physically, Mohamed gets stronger every day, but the psychological trauma he passes through and now is unimaginable.
"My fury hasn't dropped," he confesses.
In my school were little children killed.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes out a tear, comforts the child, and says: “I see my son going again. ”
He'll be able to continue his life naturally.
