I thought it was just a nostalgic thing, but it doesn't have to be like that if some kids are too young to remember vinyls like this kind of experience.
Do you have any vinyl you especially hold?
I admit I got rid of all the vinyls in the '90s.
All the vinyls I have are bought again.
I started from the idea of remaking the collection I was 15 years old, but I went beyond that limit.
The first disc I convinced my parents to buy me was Out of the Blue from the Electric Light Orchestra.
If I still had the original copy, it would have had sentimental value, but unfortunately it is somewhere through a charity store.
Steven Wilson hopes the album will be a gateway to possible new fans
Why did you launch your new Transience compilation on vinyl?
This was originally conceived as an idea for the day of the record stores, but I missed the opportunity.
My house of suggestive albums to gather some of my shorter and more accessible songs.
I became easily obsessed with the idea of doing something like "introduction into Steven Wilson's music" and I had to keep the project being launched only on vinyl.
Whoever buys the vinyl also receives a downloaded variant to high resolution.
Are you worried that the album won't show your music in its true light?
No, because, although I'm focusing on longer music, there's one thing I've always appreciated above all else: the melody part.
There is a lot of progressive rock that focuses more on technical complexity than on the melodic side.
Pink Floyd, the most famous progressive rock band of all time, passed the test due to the fact that they always put the emphasis on the melody and the atmosphere.
What are you preparing for the Albert Hall shows?
I don't want you to reveal too much.
The repertoire will be completely different in each of the nights.
In the first, there will be a version of the Hand show. Erase. which I had this year, but on steroids, with a few guests.
The second night will rather be an incursion into my history, being directed more towards fans who have been following me over the years.
How did you choose Matt Berry to open your show the second night?
And me and the others in the tournament team are great fans of [the comedy series on Channel 4] Toast of London, to the point where we always quote from him.
I thought I'd listen to Matt's music, so I bought his album, Music for Insomniacs.
I talked to him about our common love for Mike Oldfield and asked him to sing at the Royal Albert Hall.
Seems to me I'm extremely lucky to have him in the open.
You remixed albums of such bands as XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does this affect your own music?
I am not consciously inspired by this, but, inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they keep you in mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was undoubtedly the most progressive old school album I ever created.
I don't think it was a coincidence that I remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all the year before.
The current album, Hand. Erase., is much more open, because I worked at Tears for Fears and XTC.
You are often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
Is that how you feel?
You can remove the word progressive.
I think I'm probably one of the most obsessed people in today's music world and I don't say that proudly, because please believe me, it's a curse.
I think I inherited this from my father, who has an incredibly strong work ethic.
If I don't do anything all day, I'm starting to feel guilty.
That's why remix work was a gift, because it means I don't have to do my music all the time.
The music industry is a tough place to make a career.
Now I wouldn't recommend this to anyone as a profession.
I work every day and I'm not rich, but I live well.
I love what I'm doing, it's a privilege, but if I was lazy, I don't think I'd have survived.
