A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, more than 3 million people per year die prematurely due to outdoor air pollution, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is firewood and coal for heating homes and cooking, but research shows that such an alarming reason is agricultural emissions from Europe and the United States, which are the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that if no action is taken, the number of deaths - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should trigger an alarm signal for public health agencies around the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by the rain of the air are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths per year, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory disease.
Research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which is estimated to cause another 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in Nature newspaper, was the first to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths caused by these, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel power plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how pollution affects the inhabitants of China and India.
A third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of fumbling fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all being recognised dangers.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India's 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China's 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, research has found that ammonia agricultural emissions have had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Levelveld of Germany's Max Planck Chemical Institute, which led the research.
A fifth of the global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and from excessive use of fertilizers.
The ammonia reacts with the exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main reason for the deaths due to pollution of the air in the east of the United States, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Leslieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing one fifth of the deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
It only caused 5% of deaths worldwide, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
The air pollution by the power plant, especially those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the United States it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55 000 deaths per year, compared with 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid and very dusty regions, has caused almost one fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, being responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The overlap between the high level of pollution and the large number of people says their word about public health, but nothing else is known about sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," Jerrett says.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at global level.
All particles are currently supposed to be as toxic.
But if those caused by the burning of fuels are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and politicians."
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmosphere expert at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: “The study really highlights the need for air quality control, in order to avoid these deaths, especially in highly populated areas of Asia.”
